{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9cmbcj/why_some_programmers_dont_give_a_variable_a_value/", "text": "like this\nint a;\n************************* the rest", "score": 0, "comments": [{"body": "In old C you had to declare your variables at the beginning of the function, meaning you couldn't always initialize them with a meaningful value.\n\nOutside of this:\n\n\tint a; // not initialized here.\n\tif(foo()); {\n\t\ta = bar();\n\t} else {\n\t\ta = quux();\n\t}\n", "id": "e5bnr4e", "replies": [{"body": "This is actually fascinating.  I'm learning about C now and get hung up on some of these little things, it's nice to have some historical context", "id": "e5bo29d", "replies": []}]}, {"body": "Because a variable might need to be available in a broader scope, but doesn't have an appropriate value available at the time to set it as. For example, in Java(ish):\n\n    Object o;\n    try {\n        o = something();\n    } catch Exception e {\n        o = somethingElse()\n    }\n\n`o` needs to be declared outside of the `try` so it can be referenced in `catch` and afterwards, but doesn't have an appropriate starting value (besides `null` as a placeholder, but that's implict here anyways). The declaration is simply to set the scope that the variable is available in. ", "id": "e5brx4d", "replies": []}, {"body": "Saying `int a;` allocates the memory for `a`, but doesn't store anything in it. Sometimes you just want the memory up front and don't want to put anything in it yet. Maybe for performance reasons, maybe because you don't yet know what you want to store.", "id": "e5bznn9", "replies": []}, {"body": "Probably because that's what they are used to. There generally isn't a good reason to do it. Even a bit of code like this (courtesy of /u/carcigenicate): \n\n    Object o;\n    try {\n      o = something();\n    } catch Exception e {\n      o = somethingElse()\n    }\n\ncould be written as:\n\n    Object o = initializeObject();\n\n    Object initializeObject() {\n      try {\n         return something();\n      } catch (Exception e) {\n        return somethingElse();\n    }\n\nI think it's a good idea to initialize a variable where you declare it.", "id": "e5bu3uk", "replies": []}], "title": "why some programmers don't give a variable a value in the first"}